st=Snider|first=Alfred Charles|date=2015-01-11|website=Debate Motion Central|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|Won by the [[University of Botswana]], Botswana\n|-\n|8-17 December 2015\n|[[Ghana]], Accra\n|[[University of Ghana]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ug.edu.gh/news/ug-hosts-8th-pan-african-universities-debate-championship|title=UG Hosts 8th Pan-African Universities Debate Championship {{!}} University of Ghana|website=www.ug.edu.gh|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2015/December-7th/university-of-ghana-to-host-the-8th-pan-african-universities-debate-championship.php|title=University of Ghana to host the 8th Pan-African Universities Debate Championship - MyJoyOnline.com|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.ug.edu.gh/sports/ug-news/293-legon-2015-plans-and-preparations|title=LEGON 2015: Plans so far|website=apps.ug.edu.gh|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|Won by [[University of the Witwatersrand, Johannesburg]]\n|Mighti Jamie <ref>https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/917457/wits-crowned-debating-champions/</ref>\n|-\n|9-17 December 2016\n|[[Zimbabwe]], Gweru\n|[[Midlands State University]]\n|Won by [[University of the Witwatersrand, Johannesburg]]\n|-\n|7-15 December 2017\n|[[Cameroon]], Buea\n|[[University of Buea]]\n|Won by [[Midlands State University]], Zimbabwe<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ww5.msu.ac.zw/blog/2017/12/15/breaking-news-msu-crowned-2017-pan-african-universities-debate-championship-paudc-champions/|title=Breaking News: MSU Crowned 2017 Pan-African Universities Debate Championship (PAUDC) Champions|date=2017-12-15|website=Midlands State University|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|8-16 December 2018\n|[[Tanzania]], Dars es Salaam\n|[[University of Dar es Salaam|University of Dars es Salaam]]\n|Won by [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]] (KNUST)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2018/December-13th/knust-becomes-first-in-west-africa-to-win-pan-african-universities-debate-contest.php|title=KNUST becomes first in West Africa to win 'Pan African Universities Debate' contest|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|8-16 December 2019\n|[[Ghana]]. [[Kumasi]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universnewsroom.com/|title=KNUST launches 2019 Pan-African Universities Debate Championship \u2013 Radio Univers 105.7FM|last=says|first=Hans Junior|language=en|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|[[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]]\n|Won by [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]] (KNUST)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.modernghana.com/news/973801/knust-wins-pan-african-universities-debate-champio.html|title=KNUST Wins Pan African Universities Debate Championship 2nd time|website=Modern Ghana|language=en|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|Adekunbi Ademola <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://akofena-2019.herokuapp.com/PAUDC2019/tab/speaker/</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[World Universities Debating Championship|World universities debating championship]]\n*[[Literary and Debating Society (NUI Galway)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references><br />\n\n[[Category:Debating competitions]]\n[[Category:Student events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox\n |name        = Pan African Universities Debating Championship\n |bodystyle   = width:20em\n |titlestyle  = \n |title       = Pan African Universities Debating Championship\n |image = \n |caption =  \n |headerstyle = \n |labelstyle  = width:33%\n |datastyle   = \n |header1 = \n | label1 = Established\n |  data1 = 2008\n | label2 = Region\n |  data2 = Africa\n | label3 = Format\n |  data3 = [[British Parliamentary Style]]\n | label4 = Number of Teams\n |  data4 = ~80-150 \n | label5 = Record participation\n |  data5 = ~145 teams (2012)\n | label6 = Current champions\n |  data6 = [[KNUST]]\n | label7= Most championships\n |  data7 = [[University of the Witwatersrand]] (3), [[KNUST]] (2), [[University of Cape Town]] (2)\n}}\n\n'''Pan African Universities Debating Championship''' (PAUDC) is the biggest intercollegiate debate championship on the African continent established in 2008 by the [[University of Botswana]] Debate Masters Association. It is a platform that affords students from all universities within the continent to discuss issues of [[Africa]] and beyond. PAUDC is [[Parliamentary debate|parliamentary debating]] tournament held in [[British Parliamentary Style|British Parliamentary Debate]] format (involving four teams of two people in each debate).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ug.edu.gh/sports/content/university-ghana-debate-society-participate-11th-pan-african-universities-debate|title=University of Ghana Debate Society to Participate in the 11th Pan African Universities Debate Championship {{!}} UG Sports Directorate|website=www.ug.edu.gh|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.campusinformer.org/items.php?iid=1470&title=KNUST%20Looks%20For%20Second%20Straight%20Win%20When%20They%20Host%20PAUDC%202019|title=KNUST Looks For Second Straight Win When They Host PAUDC 2019 {{!}} Campus Informer|website=www.campusinformer.org|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2019/December-17th/knust-wins-pan-african-universities-debate-championship-for-second-time.php|title=KNUST wins Pan-African Universities Debate Championship for second time|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\nThe current PAUDC champions are Erasmus Sebgefia and Michael Ampah Yeboah from [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology|Kwame Nkrumah University of Science]] and Technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypercitigh.com/knust-updates/knust-debate-team-presents-pan-african-universities-debate-championship-award-to-the-vc-prof-kwasi-obiri-danso/|title=KNUST Debate Team presents Pan African Universities Debate Championship award to the VC, Prof. Kwasi Obiri Danso|date=2019-03-02|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe OSI African Regional Office and the Youth Initiative partnered with the Pan-African Universities Debating Championship (PAUDC) organizing committee and the [[University of Botswana]] to organize the first-ever Pan African Universities Debating Championship in 2008 to provide students from various African universities the opportunity to interrogate issues of African and Global importance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensocietyfoundations.org/events/inaugural-pan-african-universities-debating-championship|title=Inaugural Pan-African Universities Debating Championship|website=www.opensocietyfoundations.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internewsnetwork.com/history-of-pan-african-universities-debate-championship/|title=History of Pan African Universities Debate Championship|last=Osei|first=Jennifer|date=2020-01-01|website=Inter News Network|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n== Format ==\nThe championship is usually held in eight days. It usually takes place in the first two weeks of December and is being hosted in a different country every year\n\nThe PAUDC structure is the [[British Parliamentary Style|British Parliamentary]] (BP), made up of four teams of two, with two teams supporting a motion, and two teams opposing. Debating teams are independent and compete with each other.\n\nThe competition involves nine preliminary rounds, which become \"power-paired\" as the tournament progresses, matching the strongest-performing teams against each other. The process of scoring and pairing these teams is known as \"tabbing\". The scoring of teams is done by judges, most of whom are students or former students from the competing institutions, who return \"ballots\" with their scores to the adjudication team, led by a Chief Adjudicator who is assisted by one or more deputies.\n\nAt the end of the debate, teams are ranked from 1st to 4th.\n\nThe team names are as follows.  Opening Government (OG), consisting of the Prime Minister and Deputy Prime Minister; Opening Opposition (OO), consisting of the Opposition Leader and Deputy Opposition Leader; Closing Government (CG), consisting of the Government Member and Government Whip; and Closing Opposition (CO), consisting of the Opposition Member and the Opposition Whip.\n\nThe speaking order is Prime Minister, Opposition Leader, Deputy Prime Minister, Deputy Opposition Leader, and so forth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2018/December-13th/knust-becomes-first-in-west-africa-to-win-pan-african-universities-debate-contest.php|title=KNUST becomes first in West Africa to win 'Pan African Universities Debate' contest|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n== List of tournaments ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Host City\n!Hosting Institution\n!Winning Institution\n!Best Speaker\n|-\n|8-14 December 2008\n|[[Botswana]], [[Gaborone]]\n|[[University of Botswana]]\n|Won by the [[University of the Free State]], South Africa\n|-\n|12-18 December 2009\n|[[Botswana]], [[Gaborone]]\n|[[University of Botswana]]\n|Won by [[Rhodes University]], [[South Africa]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sundaystandard.info/rhodes-university-wins-2009-paudc-debate-champions/|title=Rhodes University wins 2009 PAUDC debate champions {{!}} Sunday Standard|last=editor|first=Online|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|4-11 December 2010\n|[[Namibia]], [[Windhoek]]\n|[[University of Namibia]]\n|Won by [[University of the Witwatersrand, Johannesburg]]\n|-\n|4-11 December 2011\n|[[Zimbabwe]], Bulawayo\n|[[Falcon College]]\n|Won by the [[University of Pretoria]], South Africa\n|-\n|9-15 December 2012\n|[[South Africa]], Pretoria\n|[[Tshwane University of Technology]]\n|Won by the [[University of Cape Town]], South Africa\n|Mighti Jamie <ref>https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/917457/wits-crowned-debating-champions/</ref>\n|-\n|November 29- December 8, 2013\n|[[Nigeria]], Calabar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tabroom.com/index/tourn/index.mhtml?webpage_id=207&tourn_id=2029|title=Tabroom.com|website=www.tabroom.com|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|[[University of Calabar]]\n|Won by the [[University of Cape Town]], South Africa\n|-\n|4-12 December 2014\n|[[South Africa]], Polokwane\n|[[University of Limpopo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uldebatingsociety.wordpress.com/2014/03/31/paudc-2014-aka-kgorong-2-0-hosted-by-the-university-of-limpopo/|title=PAUDC 2014 aka Kgorong 2.0 (Hosted by The University of Limpopo)|last=uldebatingsociety|date=2014-03-31|website=uldebatesociety|language=en|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://debatemotioncentral.blogspot.com/2015/01/pan-african-universities-debating.html|title=Debate Motion Central: Pan African Universities Debating Championship 2014|last=Snider|first=Alfred Charles|date=2015-01-11|website=Debate Motion Central|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|Won by the [[University of Botswana]], Botswana\n|-\n|8-17 December 2015\n|[[Ghana]], Accra\n|[[University of Ghana]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ug.edu.gh/news/ug-hosts-8th-pan-african-universities-debate-championship|title=UG Hosts 8th Pan-African Universities Debate Championship {{!}} University of Ghana|website=www.ug.edu.gh|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2015/December-7th/university-of-ghana-to-host-the-8th-pan-african-universities-debate-championship.php|title=University of Ghana to host the 8th Pan-African Universities Debate Championship - MyJoyOnline.com|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.ug.edu.gh/sports/ug-news/293-legon-2015-plans-and-preparations|title=LEGON 2015: Plans so far|website=apps.ug.edu.gh|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n|Won by [[University of the Witwatersrand, Johannesburg]]\n|Mighti Jamie <ref>http