onship|World universities debating championship]]\n*[[Literary and Debating Society (NUI Galway)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references><br />\n\n[[Category:Debating competitions]]\n[[Category:Student events]]\n", "name_user": "Jesien1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Where will the 2020 PAUDC be hosted", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pan_African_Universities_Debating_Championship"}
{"title_page": "JD Gaming", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports team\n| name         = JD Gaming\n| full_name    = Jingdong Gaming\n| short_name   = JDG\n| logo         = JD Gaming logo.png\n| logo_size    =\n| alt          = Logo of JD Gaming\n| caption      =\n| city         = [[Beijing]], [[China]]\n| parent_group = [[JD.com]]\n| founded      = {{start date|2017|04|df=y}}\n| folded       =\n| league       = {{nowrap|[[League of Legends Pro League|''League of Legends'' Pro League]] (LPL)}}\n| stadium      = JDG Esports Centre\n| history      =\n| ceo          = Shao \"Choice\" Xiao-Hang\n| coach        = Yoon \"Homme\" Sung-young\n| manager      = Mo \"Momo\" Jin\n| gm           =\n| partners     =\n| sport_label  = Game\n| sport        = ''[[League of Legends]]''\n| website      =\n| footnotes    =\n| fanclub      =\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| s            = \u4eac\u4e1c\u7535\u5b50\u7ade\u6280\u4ff1\u4e50\u90e8\n| t            = \u4eac\u6771\u96fb\u5b50\u7af6\u6280\u4ff1\u6a02\u90e8\n| p            = J\u012bngd\u014dng Di\u00e0nz\u01d0 J\u00ecngj\u00ec J\u00f9l\u00e8b\u00f9\n| l            = Jingdong Esports Club\n| order        = st\n}}\n\n'''JD Gaming''' ('''JDG''', also known as '''Jingdong Gaming''') is a Chinese professional [[esports]] organization based in [[Beijing]]. It has two ''[[League of Legends]]'' teams: a main roster that competes in the [[League of Legends Pro League|''League of Legends'' Pro League]] (LPL), the top level of professional ''League of Legends'' in China, and a trainee roster named Joy Dream that competes in the ''League of Legends'' Developmental League (LDL), which serves as China's secondary league. Both teams were formed on 20 May 2017 after [[e-commerce]] company [[JD.com]] acquired the LPL spot of the QG Reapers<ref name=\"MoserJingDong\">{{cite news |last1=Moser |first1=Kelsey |title=Major Chinese e-commerce site JingDong buys LPL team QG Reapers and LSPL team Now Or Never |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/major-chinese-e-commerce-site-jingdong-buys-lpl-team-qg-reapers-lspl-team-now-never-104233657.html |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=Yahoo Esports |date=20 May 2017}}</ref> and the LSPL (now LDL) spot of Now or Never.\n\nPrior to the acquisitions, JD Gaming had an all-female ''League of Legends'' team and an [[Overwatch (video game)|''Overwatch'']] team, both of which saw only minor success and were disbanded.<ref name=\"MoserJingDong\"/>\n\n== History ==\nMost of the QG Reapers' players and staff joined JD Gaming after their organization's acquisition by JD.com on 20 May 2017. JD Gaming's first roster consisted of top laner Kan \"Kabe\" Ho Man, junglers Kim \"Clid\" Tae-min and Chang \"Xinyi\" Ping, mid laner Kim \"[[Doinb (video game Player)|Doinb]]\" Tae-sang, bot laners Xu \"Barrett\" Qiu-Bin and Lee \"LokeN\" Dong-wook, and supports Hu \"Cloud\" Zhen-Wei and Zuo \"LvMao\" Ming-Hao. The team's first tournament was the 2017 Demacia Cup, which they placed ninth to twelfth after losing 0\u20132 to [[LGD Gaming]].\n\nJD Gaming was placed in Group B for the 2017 LPL Summer Split, placing fifth in their group with a 6\u201310 record.<ref>{{cite web |title=LPL/2017 Season/Summer Season |url=https://lol.gamepedia.com/LPL/2017_Season/Summer_Season |website=Leaguepedia |accessdate=21 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The team qualified for the 2017 National Electronic Sports Tournament (NEST) after defeating [[Edward Gaming]] 2\u20130 in the qualifiers. JD Gaming was able to make it to the NEST finals, where they lost 0\u20132 to [[Invictus Gaming]]. Following NEST, JD Gaming underwent several roster changes: Kabe, Xinyi, Doinb, Barrett, and Cloud left the team, while top laner Zhang \"Zoom\" Xing-Ran and mid laner Zeng \"YaGao\" Qo joined to replace the vacant positions. The newly revised roster of Zoom, Clid, YaGao, LokeN, and LvMao placed fourth in the 2017 Demacia Championship after losing 0\u20132 to Invictus Gaming once again.\n\nDuring the 2018 LPL Spring Split, JD Gaming was a member of the league's eastern conference, where they placed fourth with a 10\u20139 record.<ref>{{cite web |title=LPL/2018 Season/Spring Season |url=https://lol.gamepedia.com/LPL/2018_Season/Spring_Season |website=Leaguepedia |accessdate=21 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> This placement qualified them for playoffs, where they placed seventh to eighth overrall after losing 0\u20133 to [[Bilibili Gaming]].<ref>{{cite web |title=LPL/2018 Season/Spring Playoffs |url=https://lol.gamepedia.com/LPL/2018_Season/Spring_Playoffs |website=Leaguepedia |accessdate=21 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> JD Gaming placed third in the 2018 LPL Summer Split eastern conference with a 13\u20136 record<ref>{{cite web |title=LPL/2018 Season/Summer Season |url=https://lol.gamepedia.com/LPL/2018_Season/Summer_Season |website=Leaguepedia |accessdate=21 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and qualified for playoffs, where they placed third again after defeating [[Rogue Warriors]] 3\u20130 in the third place match.<ref>{{cite web |title=LPL/2018 Season/Summer Playoffs |url=https://lol.gamepedia.com/LPL/2018_Season/Summer_Playoffs |website=Leaguepedia |accessdate=21 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The team was unable to qualify for the [[2018 League of Legends World Championship|2018 World Championship]] after Edward Gaming knocked them out of the 2018 China Regional Finals with a close 3\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donigan |first1=Wyatt |title=EDG keeps World Championship hopes alive |url=http://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/24686732/league-legends-pro-league-edward-gaming-vs-jd-gaming |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=ESPN |date=15 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref> JD Gaming took first place at NEST 2018 after defeating [[Topsports Gaming]] 2\u20131 in the finals.\n\nClid and LokeN left JD Gaming during the offseason on 20 November 2018. In December 2018, junglers Sung \"Flawless\" Yeon-jun and \u0110\u1ed7 \"Levi\" Duy Kh\u00e1nh were acquired from Rogue Warriors and [[100 Thieves]] respectively,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Li |first1=Xing |title=Levi to head back to Asia, sign with JD Gaming |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/levi-to-head-back-to-asia-sign-with-jd-gaming |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=14 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Torres |first1=Xander |title=Levi moves over to the LPL and joins JD Gaming |url=https://www.vpesports.com/leagueoflegends/levi-moves-over-to-the-lpl-and-joins-jd-gaming |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=VPEsports |date=14 December 2018}}</ref> while bot laners Ju \"Bvoy\" Yeong-hoon and Gu \"Imp\" Seung-bin joined from Young Miracles and [[Team WE]] respectively to complete the roster. The new roster placed seventh to eighth in the 2018 Demacia Cup.\n\nJD Gaming placed eighth in the regular season of the 2019 LPL Spring Split, barely qualifying for playoffs as the last seed.<ref>{{cite web |title=LPL/2019 Season/Spring Season |url=https://lol.gamepedia.com/LPL/2019_Season/Spring_Season |website=Leaguepedia |accessdate=21 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The team went on to exceed many analysts' expectations by making it to the grand finals<ref>{{cite news |last1=Li |first1=Xing |title=JD Gaming can finish a Cinderella run in the LPL final vs. IG |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/jd-gaming-cinderella-story-ig-lpl-final |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=19 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kolev |first1=Radoslav |title=The black eight miracle: how JDG came to contest world's best team for the LPL title |url=http://vpesports.com/leagueoflegends/news/jdg-ig-lpl-finals-preview |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=VPEsports |date=19 April 2019}}</ref> after taking upset victories over Team WE, [[Royal Never Give Up]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kolev |first1=Radoslav |title=LPL playoffs: Zoom carries JDG to unlikely victory over RNG |url=https://www.vpesports.com/leagueoflegends/lpl-playoffs-zoom-carries-jdg-to-unlikely-victory-over-rng |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=VPEsports |date=6 April 2019}}</ref> and [[FunPlus Phoenix]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kolev |first1=Radoslav |title=Monstrous Gangplank sends JDG to LPL finals over FPX |url=https://www.vpesports.com/leagueoflegends/news/monstrous-gangplank-sends-jdg-to-lpl-finals-over-fpx |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=VPEsports |date=13 April 2019}}</ref> who were fifth, fourth, and first respectively in the regular season. However, JD Gaming was ultimately swept 3\u20130 by Invictus Gaming in the grand finals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yu |first1=Liang |title=Invictus Gaming defeat JD Gaming to lift maiden LPL trophy |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-04/21/c_137995978.htm |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=Xinhua |date=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Li |first1=Xing |title=Invictus Gaming sweep JDG in the LPL final |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/invictus-gaming-sweep-jdg-in-the-lpl-final |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Oak |first1=Yudae |title=League of Legends: Invictus Gaming Defeats JD Gaming in the Finals and Lifts the 2019 LPL Spring Trophy |url=https://www.invenglobal.com/articles/8067/invictus-gaming-defeats-jd-gaming-in-the-finals-and-lifts-the-2019-lpl-spring-trophy |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=Invenglobal |date=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced on 13 May 2019 that Levi and Bvoy had left JD Gaming, with the former returning to his former team, [[GAM Esports]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Endres |first1=Elena |title=Levi set to rejoin GAM Esports |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/levi-rejoin-gam-esports |accessdate=22 May 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=16 May 2019}}</ref> On 23 May 2019, jungler Seo \"Kanavi\" Jin-hyeok joined JD Gaming from [[Griffin (esports)|Griffin]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Kevin |title=Former Griffin jungler Kanavi joins JDG |url=https://korizon.net/former-griffin-jungler-kanavi-joins-jdg/ |accessdate=23 May 2019 |work=Korizon |date=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Roster ==\n\n=== Current ===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n! {{abbr|Nat.|Nationality}}\n! ID\n! Name\n! Role\n! Joined\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"color:White; background:#D61518\" | JD Gaming\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| Zoom\n| Zhang Xing-Ran\n| Top Laner\n| 21 December 2017\n|-\n| {{flagicon|South Korea}}\n| Kanavi\n| Seo Jin-hyeok\n| Jungler\n| {{abbr|28 November 2019|Rejoined after loan expired}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esuguerra |first1=Tyler |title=Kanavi rejoins JD Gaming as the League team's starting jungler |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/kanavi-rejoins-jd-gaming-as-the-league-teams-starting-jungler |accessdate=3 December 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| YaGao\n| Zeng Qi\n| Mid Laner\n| 19 December 2017\n|-\n| {{flagicon|South Korea}}\n| LokeN\n| Lee Dong-wook\n| Bot Laner\n| {{abbr|16 December 2019|Rejoined after previously leaving}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| LvMao\n| Zuo Ming-Hao\n| Support\n| 20 May 2017\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| 705\n| He Yu-Long\n| Top Laner ({{abbr|sub.|Substitute player}})\n| 17 December 2019\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| Peace\n| Lin Shang-Ren\n| Support ({{abbr|sub.|Substitute player}})\n| 17 December 2019\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| Teeen\n| Wang Yao-Ji\n| Support ({{abbr|sub.|Substitute player}})\n| 26 February 2019\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"color:White; background:#D61518\" | Joy Dream\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| sqb\n| \n| Top Laner\n| 17 August 2019\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| Dou\n| Hu Gui-Ping\n| Jungler\n| 19 June 2019\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| Sheep\n| Yang Yang\n| Jungler\n| 19 June 2019\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| A02\n| Wu Jin-Hao\n| Bot Laner\n| 26 February 2019\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| Mine\n| Tao Jun\n| Bot Laner\n| 18 April 2019\n|-\n| {{flagicon|China}}\n| Tangwa\n| Gao Ya-Ze\n| Support\n| June 2019\n|}\n\n=== Former ===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! {